passages.text: NVIDIA's FQ2 results beat \((\) 46,743M/\(\)1.05\(vs Street at\) \ \(46,231M/\) 1.01).Gaming \((\) 4.3B) was well above expectations. Datacenter \((\) 41.1B) was inline to a hair below though we note it included no China H20 contribution; compute fell a touch QoQ on H20 declines but Blackwell ramped significantly (up~17% QoQ) and networking was very strong (+46% QoQ) on rack shipments. Gross margins at 73. % were above, and included ~40 bps of benefit from release of H20 parts sold to non-China customers (gross margins and EPS would have still beat without it).

FQ3 guidance was solid \((\) 54.0B/-\(\)1.23\(vs Street\) \ \(53.5B/\) 1.21) despite including no China H20 contribution though management noted that should geopolitical issues (now more from the China side rather than US) subside they could potentially see\) \ \(2-\) 5BB in incremental China H20 sales. The bulk of the QoQ growth is driven by Datacenter (likely seen at ~\) 48B \(+\), inline-ish), with the Blackwell ramp seeing continued strength. Gross margin at 73.5% are solid, a touch above the street at 73.4%, with mid-70's still targeted for later in the year.

Overall the results were good, though with the guide perhaps just a hair light of the latest whispers, and while bears might point to computing revenues falling sequentially in the quarter and an "only" inline(ish) datacenter guide this was really just around continued messy China dynamics. But we believe guidance was still very respectable even as it continues to leave China as upside rather than count on it, and appears to indicate a sharp acceleration in the Blackwell ramp inte-next quarter suggesting core fundamentals remain robust.And the general outlook and environment overall still seem encouraging, with compute requirements moving ever upward, and Jensen suggesting potential for trillions of dollars of AI infrastructure pending by the end of the decade.
Raising estimates and rolling valuation horizon forward. We take our PT to \(\) 225\((35x,unchanged), on FY27/28 avg EPS), maintaining our Outperform rating.**
**NVDIA(OP, $225):** The datacenter opportunity is enormous, and still early, with material upside still possible.

NVIDIA's FQ2 results beat \((\) 46,743M/\\(1.05 vs Street at\) 46,231M/\\(1.01). Gaming\) ( \(4.3B) was well above expectations. Datacenter\) ( \(41.1B) was inline to a hair below though we note it included no China H20 contribution; compute fell a touch QoQ on H20 declines but Blackwell ramped significantly yup \~17% QoQ) and networking was very strong (+46% QoQ) on rack shipments. Gross margins at 73. % were above, and included \~40 bps of benefit from release of H20 parts sold to non- China customers (gross margins and EPS would have still beat without it).

Revenues of \(\) 46,743M\(were above consensus expectations\) ( \(46,231M), and guidance\) ( \(45,000M) (Exhibit 1) and included no China H20 revenues. The beat overall was driven mostly by Gaming, which reached new record levels in the quarter on the back of robust demand for new Blackwell parts and increased supply. Datacenter was a hair below given China dynamics (we suspect some sell- side numbers might have started to put it back in, estimates at least took a bit of a step- up in mid- July around the licensing announcement). ProVis beat, Auto was inline to a hair below.

Datacenter segment revenues of \(\) 41,096M\(were up\) 18\% \(QoQ and up\) 32\% \(YoY and was slightly below sell- side consensus at\) \ \(41,247M\) as revenues didn't include any China H20 contribution (though we suspect at least some sell- side numbers had begun to put it back in given estimate increases beginning in mid- July), though they did include \(\sim\) 650M in H20 sales to customers outside of China (perhaps someone was desperate for compute?) Overall H20 sales were down \(\sim\) 4B QoQ. Compute revenues were down a bit QoQ on the China H20 headwinds, but AI demand still appears robust with the Blackwell ramp continuing to show strength, with revenues growing \(\sim 17\%\) QoQ (likely to \(\) 26B+\(in the quarter, vs\) \ \(22B+\) last quarter). Networking revenues grew \(\sim 46\%\) QoQ and \(98\%\) YoY, reaching \(\) 7.25B\(in the quarter. Compute revenues totaled \~\) 33.8B (down \(1\%\) QoQ).

Gaming sales were up \(14\%\) QoQ and up \(49\%\) YoY to \(\) 4,287M\(, and were well above consensus at\) \ \(3,815M\) (Exhibit 2) with Management citing robust demand for new Blackwell parts and increasing supply.
Professional Visualization sales of \(\) 601M\(up\) 18\% \(QoQ and grew\) 32\% \(YoY, above consensus at\) \ \(532M\)
Automotive sales of \(\) 586M\(were up\) 3\% \(QoQ and up\) 69\% \(YoY, slightly below consensus at\) \ \(593M\)
OEM & IP sales came in at \(\) 173M\(for the quarter, above consensus estimates of\) \ \(111M,\) up \(56\% QoQ and up\) 97\% \(YoY (Exhibit 2 and Exhibit 3).\)

Non- GAAP Gross margins of \(72.7\%\) were above guidance of \(72\%\) and consensus at \(72.1\%\) (Exhibit 4). Note that results included a \(\sim\) 180M benefit from the release of H20 parts sold to non- China customers, excluding this benefit gross margins would be \(72.3\%\) and still above guidance and consensus.
Non- GAAP Opex of \(\) 3,795M\(were a little better than consensus\) ( \(3,905M) and below guidance at\) \ \(4.0B\)
Non- GAAP Operating margin of \(64.5\%\) was above consensus of \(63.7\%\) (Exhibit 4).
Non- GAAP tax rate came in at \(16.0\%\) below guidance of \(16.5\%\)
Non- GAAP EPS of \(\) 1.05\(, was above consensus at\) \ \(1.01\) , and excluding the H20 benefit was \(\sim\) 1.04, still above expectations.
By Segment: Graphics revenues came in at \(\) 5.4B\(this quarter, up\) 51\% \(YoY. Compute & Networking sales were\) \ \(41.3B\) , up \(56\% YOY.\)

Inventory days increased to \(\sim 105\) days (roughly \(\sim 104\) days excluding the benefit) vs 59 last quarter, and inventory dollars increased to \(\) 14,962M\(vs\) \ \(11,333M\) last quarter as management builds to support the Blackwell/Blackwell Ultra ramps (Exhibit 5).

FQ3 guidance was solid, above consensus ( \(\) 54.0B/\sim\) 1.23 vs Street \(\) 53.5B/\$ 1.21) despite including no China H20 contribution though management noted that should geopolitical issues (now more from the China side rather than US) subside they could potentially see \(\) 2- \$5B in incremental China H20 sales. The bulk of the sequential growth is driven by Datacenter (likely seen at \(\sim\) 48B+, inline- ish), with the Blackwell ramp seeing continued strength. Gross
margin at \(73.5\%\) are solid, a touch above the street at \(73.4\%\) with mid- \(70^{\circ}s\) still targeted for later in the year.

- FQ3 guidance was above consensus at \(54.0\%\) consent at \(53.5B\) (Exhibit 6), despite no expected China H20 contribution, with the bulk of sequential growth driven by Datacenter (we suspect gaming flatfish QoQ, and other end markets collectively up a bit).

- Implied datacenter guidance was solid—we believe likely in the ballpark of \(-\) 48B+ or so, roughly inline with consensus (\$48.5B) though with no contribution to China H20 sales (we suspect some sell-side numbers might have had some China in there given estimate increases that occurred in mid-July). The bulk of the QoQ growth was indicated to be due to the continued Blackwell ramp.

- Continued China datacenter headwinds are not due to US roadblocks, but rather to policies from China itself with the CFO on our callback confirming recent speculation of halted H20 production due to China governmental restrictions on purchases.
- Non-GAAP gross margins were guided to \(73.5\%\) , solid and a touch above consensus at \(73.4\%\) (Exhibit 6). The company still expects exit this year at mid-70s margins.

- Non-GAAP Opex was guided to \(4.2B\) , above consensus (\$4.06B), up \(\sim 11\%\) QoQ (Exhibit 6). For the full year, Management now expects operating expenses to grow in the high-30s range (up from prior mid-30s).
- Non-GAAP other income and expense was guided to \(-\)500M vs the Street at \(-\) 317M.
- Non-GAAP tax rate was guided to \(16.5\%\) vs the Street at \(16.4\%\) (Exhibit 6).
- NVDA implicitly guided Non-GAAP EPS next quarter to \(-\) 1.23, a touch above consensus (\$1.21) (Exhibit 6).

- Management noted that should geopolitical issues subside they could potentially see \$2-\$5B in incremental China H20 sales as some customers have received licenses in recent weeks, and they could potentially do more sales should they see more orders.

Overall the results were good, though with the guide perhaps just a hair light of the latest whispers, and while bears might point to computing revenues falling sequentially in the quarter and an "only" inline(ish) datacenter guide this was really just around continued messy China dynamics. But we believe guidance was still very respectable even as it continues to leave China as upside rather than count on it, and appears to indicate a sharp acceleration in the Blackwell ramp into next quarter suggesting core fundamentals remain robust. And the general outlook and environment overall still seem encouraging, with compute requirements moving ever upward, and Jensen suggesting potential for trillions of dollars of AI infrastructure spending by the end of the decade.

- Overall the results were good, though with the guide perhaps just a hair light of the latest whispers. We note that bears might point to computing revenues that fell in the quarter and a lower beat magnitude with datacenter outlook "only" inline(ish). However, this all still seems just really around continued messy China dynamics.

- To that end, we believe guidance was still very respectable even as it continues to leave the China opportunity as upside rather than counting on it. And we believe that parsing the outlook indicates a likely substantial acceleration in the Blackwell ramp into next quarter, potentially growing \(-\) 6-7B sequentially vs the \(-\) 4B it likely grew in FQ2 (Exhibit 7, Exhibit 8), suggesting core fundamentals remain robust.

- In the meantime demand for the company products still seems off the charts as reasoning and argentic models move into the mainstream. Rubin chips are in the fab and the platform remains on track for volume next year. We note that Jensen suggested China could be growing at 50% annually for some time (and we don't know why the rest of the world shouldn't keep up with that?). And he indicated potential for trillions of dollars of AI infrastructure spend by the end of the decade.
- The general outlook and environment overall still seems very encouraging to us.
- Capex for the quarter came in at \$1,894M.
Free cash flow for the quarter was \(\) 13.45\(B.
The company repurchased \(\) 9.7\(B in shares in the quarter.

China mix has come down substantially ( \(\sim 6\%\) of revenues in FQ226 vs \(\sim 13\%\) of revenues in FQ126; Exhibit 9) given lost H20 revenues, with China datacenter sales indicated as LSD % of datacenter revenues (we assume some networking etc).

We update our model, raising estimates, and roll our valuation horizon forward. We increase our price target to \(\) 225\(PT (35x, unchanged, on FY27 / CY26 EPS), and maintain our Outperform rating.\)

We update our model, and raise estimates. Given we are now halfway through the fiscal year we also roll our valuation horizon forward from FY27 to the average of FY27/ FY28 (to approximate a forward 12- month horizon one year from today, as is our practice).
We raise our FY2026 revenue estimate from \(\) 190.4\(B to\) \ \(202.7B\) , FY2027 from \(\) 226.6B\(to\) \ \(247.6B\) , and FY2028 from \(\) 256.4B\(to\) \ \(281.5B\)
We raise our FY2026 non- GAAP EPS estimate from \(\) 4.11\(to\) \ \(4.44\) , FY2027 from \(\) 5.36\(to\) \ \(5.84\) , and FY2028 from \(\) 6.20\(to\) \ \(6.82\)
We increase our target price to \(\) 225\((- 35x, unchanged, applied to average FY27 / FY28 non - GAAP EPS estimate at\) \ \(6.33\)
We maintain our Outperform rating.
